   742→## Patterns …
   857→#### `P._` wildcard
   859→The `P._` pattern will match any value. You can also use `P.any`, which is an alias to `P._`.
   860→
   861→```ts
   862→import { match, P } from 'ts-pattern';
   863→
   864→const input = 'hello';
   865→
   866→const output = match(input)
   867→  .with(P._, () => 'It will always match')
   868→  // OR
   869→  .with(P.any, () => 'It will always match')
   870→  .otherwise(() => 'This string will never be used');
   871→
   872→console.log(output);
   873→// => 'It will always match'
   874→```
   875→
